IMF needs more Lagarde
Davos—Lagarde has said she is open to another five-year term as head of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
She should stay.
The IMF has never had a better leadership than under her; the IMF’s board should give her the opportunity to finish the work she started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, inheriting a troubled institution.
2008年的全球金融危机及其后续经济影响使西方领导的多边贷款机构和自由市场的“华盛顿共识”声名狼藉。
拉加德的领导帮助国际货币基金组织恢复了声誉。
许多人关注她的个人品质——理所应当。
她坦率、有力、温暖且富有魅力。
与她会面的各国官员（通常是在微妙的情况下见面）纷纷表示她敢于直言不讳，同时也是一位敏锐的倾听者。
For an institution leader who must negotiate terms rather than dominate everything, these are important qualities.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed restructuring or they would have to build firewalls to prevent financial contagion. The bitter medicine was taken.
Similarly, she loudly advocated providing IMF support to some countries — such as Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine — which is crucial for global stability.
There are countless other examples.
The IMF is not good at innovation and is usually not passionate either.
Lagarde started to change that.
In the process, she gave this institution, often known for bitter medicine, a more humane face.
For example, helping manage the Middle East refugee crisis was not originally part of the IMF's mandate.
But under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its programs so that the Jordanian government could allocate more funds towards helping the displaced (over one million Syrians and Iraqis living in camps within Jordan).
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola outbreak hit West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF to use its available resources to provide debt relief to affected countries, enabling them to raise the pay of doctors and nurses – a first for the IMF to use its capital in this way.
Moreover, Lagarde recognized three major challenges facing the world today and took action against them.
First, she strongly advocated for including more women in the labor force, herself being a role model of the value of women in leadership positions.
In countries ranging from Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urged leaders to stop wasting such a huge talent resource—and thereby realize economic potential.
Second, under her leadership, the IMF also addressed the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not just a matter of basic fairness.
IMF research underscores the direct link between reducing income inequality and boosting economic growth.
While not the first institution to establish this connection, the IMF's stature makes it particularly pressing.
Lagarde has been personally dedicated to promoting this idea, which has heightened its urgency.
Third, Lagarde played a significant role in helping the world understand the full impact of technological change – some of which will have frighteningly disruptive effects.
For instance, automation will continue to enhance manufacturing efficiency and reduce costs, but also means that fewer jobs will be created as a result of economic growth compared to before.
This emerging reality's political, economic, and social consequences are worth our recognition and serious study.
Lagarde made the IMF central to this work.
Critics might say it is time for developing countries to lead the IMF.
After all, Lagarde is the 11th European to hold this position in a row, and such privilege for Europe is hard to justify in today's world.
Some might also argue that the austerity the IMF supported in Greece has not been entirely effective, indicating that she has lost touch with the general public.
Still, some point out that she faces allegations of involvement in financial scandals with France, which could distract her from her work at the IMF.
Following her predecessor Dominique Strauss-Kahn's scandal, critics argue that the IMF cannot afford another similar distraction.
Let us examine each of these objections one by one.
The IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from beyond Europe and the United States.
But the aim of ending this Western privilege is to have the selection process based on merit rather than political considerations.
{s} Lagarde is the best candidate for the IMF director, and emerging forces such as the BRICS (Brazil, Russia, India, and China) have not joined to promote an alternative.
The fact that a European serves as the IMF director may also have been one of the favorable factors for the IMF's decision last year to include the renminbi in the basket of currencies determining the value of its special drawing rights.
Furthermore, Lagarde's impressive political flexibility ultimately convinced both Republicans and Democrats in the US Congress to approve IMF governance reforms, which not only bolstered the IMF's arsenal against financial crises but also more accurately reflected the changing dynamics of the global economy.
For instance, now the BRICS countries already rank among the top ten shareholders of the IMF.
Last year, Lagarde made some personally colorful and forthright – though some believe inappropriate – comments on the Greek issue.
But she is not the one who brings economic pain to Greece; her tenure at the IMF fully demonstrates that no IMF Managing Director has done as much to lead the Fund in its efforts to alleviate the suffering of people in crisis.
Finally, France's charges against Lagarde were opposed by the French Prosecutor General, and Lagarde was at most only tangentially involved.
The world needs a leader committed to making the world safer and more prosperous.
Lagarde has already shown herself to be such a leader, dedicated to making the IMF fit for the 21st century.
She should be given the opportunity to do so from start to finish.
